{"key":"processedPost-15767744","value":{"id":15767744,"first":15767034,"last":15774650,"when":1328548102,"utime":"02/06/12 07:08 PM","content":"P value is not a real indicator of mycelium age, and I no longer use it.&nbsp; You want to take samples before the mycelium grows to the edges of the petri for two reasons:&nbsp; One is to make sure the culture is as young as possible, and the other reason is that once the culture reaches the edge of the petri, microscopic strands of mycelium make it through whatever wrapping you use for gas exchange, and exposes the mycelium to contaminant spores.<br />I'd take a fresh culture from the slant, and then grab a new culture when it's only grown about 1 inch total on the petri dish, but still far from the edge.&nbsp; Use it to make new slants.<br />RR","title":"Re: Question bout cultures and timing"}}